<i>[Girl Hums, Rips Paper]</i>

15
00:02:58,560 --> 00:03:03,580
<i>[Birds Chirping]</i>

16
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:12,260
<i>[Woman Narrating]
Maycomb was a tired, old town,</i>

17
00:03:12,340 --> 00:03:16,430
<i>even in 1932
when l first knew it.</i>

18
00:03:16,510 --> 00:03:19,770
<i>Some how it was hotter then.</i>

19
00:03:19,840 --> 00:03:23,440
<i>Men's stiff collars wilted
by 9:00 in the morning.</i>

20
00:03:23,510 --> 00:03:28,280
<i>Ladies bathed before noon,
after their 3:00 naps...</i>

21
00:03:28,350 --> 00:03:31,120
<i>and by night fall
were like soft tea cakes...</i>

22
00:03:31,190 --> 00:03:34,120
<i>with frostings of sweat
and sweet talcum.</i>

23
00:03:35,530 --> 00:03:40,460
<i>The day was 24 hours long,
but it seemed longer.</i>

24
00:03:40,530 --> 00:03:42,800
<i>There was no hurry,
for there was nowhere to go...</i>

25
00:03:42,870 --> 00:03:45,960
<i>and nothing to buy:;
no money to buy it with.</i>

26
00:03:46,040 --> 00:03:48,300
<i>Although Maycomb County
had recently been told...</i>

27
00:03:48,370 --> 00:03:52,310
<i>that it had nothing to fear
but fear itself.</i>

28
00:03:52,380 --> 00:03:55,310
<i>That summer
I was six years old.</i>

29
00:03:55,380 --> 00:03:59,150
<i>- Good morning, Mr. Cunningham.
- Good morning, miss.</i>

30
00:03:59,220 --> 00:04:02,910
<i>My daddy's getting dressed.
Would you like me to call him for you?</i>

31
00:04:02,990 --> 00:04:06,920
<i>- I don't care to bother.
- Why, it's no bother, Mr. Cunningham.</i>

32
00:04:06,990 --> 00:04:09,690
<i>He'll be happy to see you.
Atticus!</i>

33
00:04:12,160 --> 00:04:14,430
<i>Atticus?</i>

34
00:04:14,500 --> 00:04:16,760
<i>It's Mr. Cunningham.</i>

35
00:04:18,170 --> 00:04:21,260
<i>- Good morning, Walter.
- Good morning, Mr. Finch.</i>

36
00:04:21,340 --> 00:04:24,000
<i>I didn't want to bother you none.</i>

37
00:04:24,070 --> 00:04:27,100
<i>I brung you these here hickory nuts
as part of my entailment.</i>

38
00:04:27,180 --> 00:04:30,940
<i>Well, I thank you. The collards
we had last week were delicious.</i>

39
00:04:31,020 --> 00:04:32,950
<i>Well, Morning.</i>

40
00:04:33,020 --> 00:04:34,950
<i>Morning.</i>

41
00:04:38,520 --> 00:04:43,120
<i>Scout, I think maybe, uh,
next time Mr. Cunningham comes,</i>

42
00:04:43,190 --> 00:04:45,130
<i>you'd better not call me.</i>

43
00:04:45,200 --> 00:04:48,290
<i>- I thought you'd want to thank him.
- Oh, I do.</i>

44
00:04:48,370 --> 00:04:51,960
<i>I think it embarrasses him
to be thanked.</i>

45
00:04:56,370 --> 00:04:58,810
<i>Why does he bring you
all this stuff?</i>

46
00:04:58,880 --> 00:05:01,470
<i>He's paying me for some legal work
I did for him.</i>

47
00:05:01,550 --> 00:05:03,570
<i>Why does he pay you like this?</i>

48
00:05:03,650 --> 00:05:06,340
<i>That's the only way he can.
He has no money.</i>

49
00:05:06,420 --> 00:05:08,750
<i>- Is he poor?
- Yes.</i>

50
00:05:10,990 --> 00:05:13,080
<i>Are we poor?</i>

51
00:05:13,160 --> 00:05:15,250
<i>We are, indeed.</i>

52
00:05:15,330 --> 00:05:18,090
<i>Are we as poor
as the Cunninghams?</i>

53
00:05:18,160 --> 00:05:20,260
<i>No, not exactly.</i>

54
00:05:20,330 --> 00:05:23,270
<i>Cunninghams are
country folks, farmers.</i>

55
00:05:23,330 --> 00:05:27,100
<i>- The crash hit them the hardest.
- [ Screen Door Squeaks ]</i>

56
00:05:27,170 --> 00:05:29,260
<i>Scout, call your brother.</i>

57
00:05:29,340 --> 00:05:32,610
<i>[ Scout ]
Atticus? Jem's up in the tree.</i>

58
00:05:32,680 --> 00:05:36,340
<i>He says he won't come down
until you agree to play football
for the Methodists.</i>

59
00:05:39,780 --> 00:05:41,720
<i>Jem?</i>

60
00:05:44,690 --> 00:05:49,130
<i>Son, why don't you come down out
of there now and have your breakfast.</i>

61
00:05:49,190 --> 00:05:51,630
<i>Calpurnia has a good one.
Hot biscuits.</i>

62
00:05:51,700 --> 00:05:54,960
<i>[ Jem ] Not 'til you agree
to play football for the Methodists.</i>

63
00:05:55,030 --> 00:05:59,970
<i>Oh, son, I can't do that.
I explained to you I'm too old to get out there.</i>

64
00:06:00,040 --> 00:06:02,900
<i>After all,
I'm the only father you have.</i>

65
00:06:02,970 --> 00:06:05,340
<i>Wouldn't want me to get out there and get
my head knocked off, would you?</i>

66
00:06:05,410 --> 00:06:07,540
<i>I ain't comin' down.</i>

67
00:06:08,810 --> 00:06:11,080
<i>Suit yourself.</i>

68
00:06:14,450 --> 00:06:16,390
<i>[ Woman ]
Good morning.</i>

69
00:06:17,660 --> 00:06:19,590
<i>Good morning,
Miss Maudie.</i>

70
00:06:19,660 --> 00:06:24,620
<i>- What's going on over there?
- I'm having a terrible time,
Miss Maudie.</i>

71
00:06:24,700 --> 00:06:28,360
<i>Jem's stayin' up in the tree
until Atticus agrees to play
football for the Methodists.</i>

72
00:06:28,430 --> 00:06:31,920
<i>And Atticus says
he's too old.</i>

73
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:34,990
<i>Every time I want him
to do something, he's too old.</i>

74
00:06:35,070 --> 00:06:37,100
<i>He's too old for anything!</i>

75
00:06:37,170 --> 00:06:39,940
<i>[ Maudie ]
He can do plenty of things.</i>

76
00:06:40,010 --> 00:06:43,450
<i>You be good, children.
Mind Cal.</i>

77
00:06:43,510 --> 00:06:46,950
<i>- Morning, Maudie.
- Morning, Atticus.</i>

78
00:06:47,020 --> 00:06:49,110
<i>He won't let me have a gun,</i>

79
00:06:49,190 --> 00:06:53,020
<i>and he'll only play
touch football with me, never tackle.</i>

80
00:06:53,090 --> 00:06:58,120
<i>He can make somebody's will
so airtight, you can't break it.</i>

81
00:06:58,200 --> 00:07:02,290
<i>You count your blessings
and stop complaining, both of you.</i>

82
00:07:02,370 --> 00:07:05,460
<i>Thank your stars
he has the sense to act his age.</i>

83
00:07:05,540 --> 00:07:09,060
<i>- Jem, he is pretty old.
- I can't help that.</i>

84
00:07:12,710 --> 00:07:15,740
<i>Hey.</i>

85
00:07:18,320 --> 00:07:20,340
<i>Hey, yourself.</i>

86
00:07:20,420 --> 00:07:23,850
<i>I'm Charles Baker Harris.
I can read.</i>

87
00:07:23,920 --> 00:07:27,410
<i>You got anything needs readin',
I can do it.</i>

88
00:07:27,490 --> 00:07:30,360
<i>How old are you?
Four and a half?</i>

89
00:07:30,430 --> 00:07:33,590
<i>- Goin' on seven.
- No wonder then.</i>

90
00:07:33,660 --> 00:07:35,930
<i>Scout's been readin'
since she was born,</i>

91
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:38,930
<i>and she don't start school
'til next month.</i>

92
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:41,600
<i>You look right puny
for goin' on seven.</i>

93
00:07:41,670 --> 00:07:44,110
<i>I'm little, but I'm old.</i>

94
00:07:44,170 --> 00:07:46,770
<i>Folks call me Dill.</i>

95
00:07:46,840 --> 00:07:48,940
<i>I'm from Meridian, Mississippi.</i>

96
00:07:49,010 --> 00:07:52,950
<i>I'm spending two weeks next door
with my Aunt Stephanie.</i>

97
00:07:53,020 --> 00:07:55,680
<i>My mama worked for a photographer
in Meridian.</i>

98
00:07:55,750 --> 00:08:00,780
<i>She entered my picture
in the "Beautiful Child" contest
and won five dollars on me.</i>

99
00:08:00,860 --> 00:08:06,230
<i>She give the money to me, and I went
to the picture show 20 times with it.</i>

100
00:08:06,300 --> 00:08:10,100
<i>- Our mama's dead, but we got a daddy.
- Where's your daddy?</i>

101
00:08:10,170 --> 00:08:14,100
<i>- I haven't got one.
- Is he dead?</i>

102
00:08:14,170 --> 00:08:16,400
<i>[ Dill ]
No.</i>

103
00:08:16,470 --> 00:08:20,810
<i>Well, if he's not dead,
you've got one, haven't you?</i>

104
00:08:23,050 --> 00:08:26,070
<i>- [ Screen Door Squeaks ]
- Hush, Scout.</i>

105
00:08:27,650 --> 00:08:30,590
<i>[ Softly ]
What did I do? What did I do?</i>

106
00:08:32,820 --> 00:08:35,260
<i>Dill, this is Calpurnia.</i>

107
00:08:35,330 --> 00:08:37,260
<i>Pleased to know you, Dill.</i>

108
00:08:37,330 --> 00:08:39,390
<i>[ Dill ]
Pleased to know you.</i>

109
00:08:39,460 --> 00:08:41,590
<i>My daddy owns
the L&N Railroad.</i>

110
00:08:41,670 --> 00:08:45,100
<i>He's gonna let me run the engine
all the way to New Orleans.</i>

111
00:08:45,170 --> 00:08:47,100
<i>Is that so?</i>

112
00:08:49,010 --> 00:08:51,600
<i>- [ Dill ]
He says I can invite anybody--
- Shh.</i>

113
00:08:51,680 --> 00:08:55,940
<i>[ Footsteps ]</i>

114
00:08:56,010 --> 00:08:58,850
<i>There goes the meanest man
that ever took a breath of life.</i>

115
00:09:02,950 --> 00:09:05,890
<i>Why is he the meanest man?</i>

116
00:09:05,960 --> 00:09:09,220
<i>Well, for one thing,</i>

117
00:09:09,290 --> 00:09:11,890
<i>he has a boy named Boo...</i>

118
00:09:11,960 --> 00:09:15,260
<i>that he keeps chained to a bed
in the house over yonder.</i>

119
00:09:17,840 --> 00:09:19,530
<i>Come on.</i>

120
00:09:24,810 --> 00:09:27,400
<i>See? He lives over there.</i>

121
00:09:27,480 --> 00:09:29,570
<i>Boo only comes out
at night...</i>

122
00:09:29,650 --> 00:09:32,910
<i>when you're asleep
and it's pitch dark.</i>

123
00:09:32,980 --> 00:09:35,140
<i>When you wake up at night,
you can hear him.</i>

124
00:09:35,220 --> 00:09:37,920
<i>Once I heard him scratching
on our screen door,</i>

125
00:09:37,990 --> 00:09:41,390
<i>but he was gone
by the time Atticus got there.</i>

126
00:09:41,460 --> 00:09:44,790
<i>Wonder what he does in there.</i>

127
00:09:44,860 --> 00:09:47,800
<i>Wonder what he looks like.</i>

128
00:09:47,870 --> 00:09:51,600
<i>Well...
judging from his tracks,</i>

129
00:09:51,670 --> 00:09:54,300
<i>he's about
six and a half feet tall.</i>

130
00:09:54,370 --> 00:09:58,640
<i>He eats raw squirrels
and all the cats he can catch.</i>

131
00:09:58,710 --> 00:10:02,770
<i>There's a long, jagged scar
that runs all the way across his face.</i>

132
00:10:02,850 --> 00:10:04,840
<i>His teeth are yellow and rotten.</i>

133
00:10:04,920 --> 00:10:09,110
<i>His eyes are popped,
and he drools most of the time.</i>

134
00:10:10,350 --> 00:10:12,880
<i>Oh, I don't believe you.</i>

135
00:10:12,960 --> 00:10:15,480
<i>Dill, what are you doing here?</i>

136
00:10:15,560 --> 00:10:18,050
<i>My Lord, Aunt Stephanie!
You almost gave me a heart attack!</i>

137
00:10:18,130 --> 00:10:20,460
<i>Dill, I don't want you playing
around that house over there.</i>

138
00:10:20,530 --> 00:10:22,830
<i>There is a maniac who lives there,
and he's dangerous.</i>

139
00:10:22,900 --> 00:10:27,300
<i>See? I was trying to warn him
about Boo, but he wouldn't believe me.</i>

140
00:10:27,370 --> 00:10:29,640
<i>You'd just better believe him,
Mr. Dill Harris.</i>

141
00:10:29,710 --> 00:10:31,870
<i>Tell him about the time Boo
tried to kill his papa.</i>

142
00:10:31,940 --> 00:10:36,310
<i>I was standing in my yard
when his mama come out yelling,
"He's killing us all!"</i>

143
00:10:36,380 --> 00:10:40,150
<i>Turned out that Boo was sitting
in the living room cutting up
the paper for his scrapbook,</i>

144
00:10:40,220 --> 00:10:42,810
<i>and when his daddy came by,
he reached over with his scissors,</i>

145
00:10:42,890 --> 00:10:46,220
<i>stabbed him in his leg, pulled them out
and went right on cutting the paper.</i>

146
00:10:46,290 --> 00:10:48,260
<i>They wanted to send him
to an asylum,</i>

147
00:10:48,330 --> 00:10:51,590
<i>but his daddy said,
"No Radley is going to any asylum."</i>

148
00:10:51,660 --> 00:10:53,820
<i>So they locked him up
in the basement of the courthouse...</i>

149
00:10:53,900 --> 00:10:55,830
<i>'til he nearly died of the damp...</i>

150
00:10:55,900 --> 00:10:57,870
<i>and his daddy
brought him back home.</i>

151
00:10:57,940 --> 00:11:01,800
<i>There he is to this day,
sitting over there with his scissors.</i>

152
00:11:01,870 --> 00:11:04,600
<i>Lord knows what
he's doing or thinking.</i>

153
00:11:07,010 --> 00:11:07,340
<i>[ Shouting ]
Six, seven, eight,</i>

154
00:11:07,340 --> 00:11:10,940
<i>[ Shouting ]
Six, seven, eight,</i>

155
00:11:11,010 --> 00:11:14,780
<i>- [ Bell Tolling ]
- nine, ten!</i>

156
00:11:14,850 --> 00:11:18,450
<i>[ Tolling Continues ]</i>

157
00:11:18,520 --> 00:11:21,120
<i>Come on, Scout!
It's 5:00!</i>

158
00:11:24,860 --> 00:11:28,300
<i>- Where you going?
- Time to meet Atticus.</i>

159
00:11:28,370 --> 00:11:31,300
<i>- Why do you call your daddy Atticus?
- 'Cause Jem does.</i>

160
00:11:31,370 --> 00:11:33,800
<i>- Why does he?
- I don't know.</i>

161
00:11:33,870 --> 00:11:36,700
<i>He just started to
ever since he began talking.</i>

162
00:11:36,770 --> 00:11:38,710
<i>[ Spits ]</i>

163
00:11:40,610 --> 00:11:42,810
<i>Wait. Stop.</i>

164
00:11:42,880 --> 00:11:45,140
<i>- Miss Dubose is on her porch.
- [ Groans ]</i>

165
00:11:45,220 --> 00:11:48,810
<i>Listen, no matter what she says to you,
don't answer her back.</i>

166
00:11:48,890 --> 00:11:51,650
<i>There's a Confederate pistol
in her lap under her shawl,</i>

167
00:11:51,720 --> 00:11:53,990
<i>and she'll kill you
quick as look at you.</i>

168
00:11:54,060 --> 00:11:55,990
<i>Come on.</i>

169
00:12:03,830 --> 00:12:07,430
<i>- Hey, Miss Dubose.
- Don't you say "hey" to me,
you ugly girl!</i>

170
00:12:07,500 --> 00:12:10,960
<i>You say,
"Good afternoon, Miss Dubose."</i>

171
00:12:11,040 --> 00:12:13,600
<i>You come over here
when I'm talking to you.</i>

172
00:12:13,680 --> 00:12:16,770
<i>- You come over here, I said!
- Hi, Atticus.</i>

173
00:12:16,850 --> 00:12:20,110
<i>- [ Dubose Continues Shouting ]
- Atticus, this is Dill.
He's Miss Stephanie's nephew.</i>

174
00:12:20,180 --> 00:12:22,120
<i>[ Dubose ] Doesn't your daddy
teach you to respect old people?</i>

175
00:12:22,190 --> 00:12:25,310
<i>You come back here,
Jean Louise Finch!</i>

176
00:12:25,390 --> 00:12:28,790
<i>Good afternoon, Miss Dubose.</i>

177
00:12:28,860 --> 00:12:33,060
<i>My, you look like
a picture this afternoon.</i>

178
00:12:33,130 --> 00:12:35,530
<i>[ Scout Whispers ]
He don't say a picture of what.</i>

179
00:12:35,600 --> 00:12:38,120
<i>My goodness gracious,
look at your flowers.</i>

180
00:12:38,200 --> 00:12:41,140
<i>Have you ever seen
anything more beautiful?</i>

181
00:12:41,200 --> 00:12:45,660
<i>Miss Dubose,
the gardens at Bellingrath
have nothing to compare...</i>

182
00:12:45,740 --> 00:12:47,800
<i>with your flowers.</i>

183
00:12:47,880 --> 00:12:50,810
<i>I don't think they're
as nice as last year.</i>

184
00:12:50,880 --> 00:12:54,480
<i>He gets her interested in something nice
so she forgets to be mean.</i>

185
00:12:54,550 --> 00:12:57,650
<i>Your yard is going to be
the showplace of this town.</i>

186
00:12:57,720 --> 00:13:01,660
<i>Well, grand seeing you,
Miss Dubose.</i>

187
00:13:14,500 --> 00:13:16,770
<i>"l had two cats...</i>

188
00:13:16,840 --> 00:13:19,780
<i>which I brought ashore...</i>

189
00:13:19,840 --> 00:13:23,280
<i>on my first raft.</i>

190
00:13:23,350 --> 00:13:26,910
<i>And I had a dog."</i>

191
00:13:28,820 --> 00:13:34,280
<i>Atticus, do you think Boo Radley
ever really comes and looks
in my window at night?</i>

192
00:13:34,360 --> 00:13:39,950
<i>- Jem says he does. This afternoon
when we were over by their house--
- Scout...</i>

193
00:13:40,030 --> 00:13:44,470
<i>I told you and Jem
to leave those poor people alone.</i>

194
00:13:44,530 --> 00:13:46,630
<i>I want you to stay away
from their house...</i>

195
00:13:46,700 --> 00:13:48,360
<i>and stop tormenting them.</i>

196
00:13:48,440 --> 00:13:49,960
<i>Yes, sir.</i>

197
00:13:50,040 --> 00:13:52,980
<i>That's all the reading
for tonight, honey. It's getting late.</i>

198
00:13:53,040 --> 00:13:56,810
<i>- What time is it?
- 8:30.</i>

199
00:13:56,880 --> 00:13:58,850
<i>May I see your watch?</i>

200
00:14:17,400 --> 00:14:20,930
<i>"To Atticus,
my beloved husband."</i>

201
00:14:22,510 --> 00:14:25,940
<i>Atticus, Jem says this watch
is gonna belong to him someday.</i>

202
00:14:26,010 --> 00:14:29,170
<i>- That's right.
- Why?</i>

203
00:14:29,250 --> 00:14:33,270
<i>Well...
it's customary...</i>

204
00:14:33,350 --> 00:14:35,610
<i>for the boy to have
his father's watch.</i>

205
00:14:35,690 --> 00:14:39,140
<i>What are you gonna give me?</i>

206
00:14:42,690 --> 00:14:47,460
<i>I don't know that I have
much else of value that belongs to me.</i>

207
00:14:49,870 --> 00:14:52,460
<i>But there's a pearl necklace,</i>

208
00:14:52,540 --> 00:14:55,970
<i>there's a ring that
